Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have a total of 29 percent
According to the preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party, where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer was seriously threatened, suffered particularly large losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria, the governor of Carinthia, Joerg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at national level.
According to the preliminary results, the Socialists remain, with 29.8 per cent of the vote, the country's first political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 per cent of the vote.
The SVP, which at 25.6 percent loses nearly nine percent of the vote, finished even worse.
These were the worst results of the two major parties in the post-war period; especially for the People's Party, which had called the early elections, the result was literally catastrophic.
Even in early July, when the zVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SP.
But voters are visibly chastising them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations about the possible resignation of the party leader and current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer were uttered.
Observers believe that this could happen on Monday, at the party’s extraordinary board of directors.
Such a development would a priori facilitate the way towards the outcome of the outcome of the election, which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the grand coalition, the SP- and 'VP' coalition.
Nevertheless, in view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the free parties would have obtained 18 per cent and the B' 11 per cent of the votes - the Socialists at the same time expressed the fear of a 1999 repetition, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPO was still unified, it was in 2005 that the Beg separated itself) on a common government.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he is planning to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently to highlight this development.
The last party to have access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell back from the third in the third to fifth place.
Clearly, no other party crossed the four-percentage limit and did not accede to parliament.
An extreme struggle: MP3 readers against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
The result is clearly that it is better to buy only a telephone.
However, there are sufficient reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way in which the future owner is used and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are crammed vinyl records in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same applies to music during the movement, namely compressed music, to put it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here, too, there are categories according to price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 kroons on a reader, just as a fan of Pink Floyd would have difficulty supporting earphones bought for twenty kroons at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The lifetime of batteries is also decisive
Some top-of-the-range music players are capable of many more things than simple music playback, but these are unknown functions, of course, most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephone calls and the sending of SMS, he is able to read music and films, to record them, he has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, until he is used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a little computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing almost a miracle.
However, the universal nature of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two rechargings.
And reading music is one of the most important energy goofers.
Rare mobile phones are able to read music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is much lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary) perform much better.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you may call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharging for work - this being valid even for more expensive devices.
Problem will not arise for MP3 readers, who are capable, following reloading, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least efficient.
Another problem arises when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, since a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all of them can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
It is possible, of course, to record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in the mobile devices.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need, except in exceptions (iPod), any software.
All you have to do is fill, through the USB connector, the music device coming from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a classified media library based on the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the user's judgment.
Some devices display only an index having a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, be particularly interested in the lifetime of the accumulator, in the capacity of the memory, in the quality and type of output of sound and, of course, in the ease of control.
If the music is essentially for you, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading MP3.
Virtually all mobile phones are capable of doing so today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player is able to read.
All of them manage to read MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have precisely this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA music.
AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods), on the other hand, is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding operator's web pages (or those of another supplier) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to obtain a musical mobile.
Unfortunately, the operator's offer is miserable and is, in most cases, limited to rapidly made radio tubes.
Prices are also not the lowest.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the Internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motives in on themselves.
Every time you feel like listening to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, when you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always carry earphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in loudspeakers, which almost all mobile phones have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music motives is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand kroner, one can have an already very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best telephones and the best equipped, also with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to order the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the control with that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or of a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. The Vodafone 527) generally has a slot for exchangeable memory cards (the M2 type, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you are not going to exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support in principle only maps with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones do even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton, or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 kroons.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose more specialized walk-and-moped devices (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These apparatuses are provided with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the control is similar to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer life of the accumulator (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) is provided by an MP3 reader produced by one of the marks mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not miss him for long.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz many times the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher at home than in the rest of the Union, has confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the field of roaming charge regulation, there is a danger of paradoxical situation - SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic continue to be so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may sound paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this respect, Pavel Dvook, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, who has stated on several occasions that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network apparently no longer has much chance (by the way, now it would find only difficult frequencies).
Now, there is still a possibility--a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market which has led to a considerable fall in prices, which were to which conventional operators were to react subsequently as well.
Yet, even before the entry of troubled festivals such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was room for such operators and that they could be a real success.
Moreover, we do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100 000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Let us add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns the U:fon in Thusha.
The advantage of virtual operators being the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they do indeed need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, free from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
For example, in the world, virtual operators are emerging as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and text messages, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Britain at least half as much as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
'True men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust,' said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Vodafone's spokesperson Miroslav 'epick', he doubted: 'The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
All the more so as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
It seems almost certain, however, that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
'We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations are not very promoters.
Instead, the launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said Mobil.cz Jana Studnykov, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not concealed, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
The future may therefore be promising.
From unofficial information, it seems that we could perhaps welcome the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the time being, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
'At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to others very specific.
For the time being, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr.e. of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrova says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: 'We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis.'
She adds: 'It is practically excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Instead, Vodafone focuses its attention on fulfilling queries to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav zepick says in relation to this: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
That is what we believe means the most input from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.'
The responsible authorities: in tune with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a fall in prices and thus a fall in their profit.
What, then, is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to understand themselves as thieves in fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the T-T, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is reflected in the public information available from the web pages of the T.
Nowadays, however, the U:fon lends itself to serve as an argument so as not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrova noted: 'Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators, the indifference of Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, it is not just a question of the attitude of the T, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately, has not, in the Czech Republic, the power to intervene in economic competition.
It is the exclusive responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (AOHS).
However, the latter adopted its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, as the offer of the potential concerned has a priori not presented sufficient interest to the traditional operators," said in response to our question Kristiin Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the OHS.
A statement made in this way would not come as a surprise from operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care, so that no one benefits from its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
All the more so since Kristion Chalupa adds: 'At a foreign level, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a fall in the prices of mobile telephone services.'
However, exerting pressure on the honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not one of the interests of the company.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
Similarly, a price of gas exactly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and the hard battle of competition.
"The Office has not noticed any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this respect, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their market behaviour.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even to the telecommunications regulator," said Chaloupa in its statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the "T" according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator has a fairly logical monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without accepting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the zOHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many stakeholders (including the already mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they face similar constraints in the negotiations with all operators.
Overcoming responsibility on the T is a fairly common turn in communications, whereby the zh.S. washs its hands from the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to bring about the recent new generation of the telecommunications law, which has been adopted, to extend the powers of the "T-plus" in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the OHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently different.
When no one is watching, it can work
However, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operator, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but mobile telephone services are only partly public.
In most cases, it is about firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specialised mobile telephone services are thus offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected representatives.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company is in front of the operator is a conventional business customer, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As a major customer, it obtains special (and other) quota offers.
What is a problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
'If it happened what you are talking about, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would examine and which could lead to a stoppage of the collaboration with the company in question,' replied our question about this problem, Martina Kemrov.
However, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it may be thousands of customers.
Auncun operator, however, does not act against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and, at the same time, as opposed to genuine virtual operators, they do not in any way threaten them with their own official marketing.
The problems are mentioned as follows: 'The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary mobile operators' customers."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the T.
In addition, another question arises at the zOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the company has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such activity, and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who say they have no idea that this would happen, as their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable fall in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators were trying, sometimes more and less so, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market that was too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies intervened in the developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up obtaining the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators deal with this issue in the manner of a hot potato that is discarded by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw away the sleeve after the bump.
If the slide information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear here, the Czech mobile market may be getting back on track.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult to remain impassive in the face of rejection (discrimination) by others.
And we will perhaps stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolinek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jio Bolohlokek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, a choir-like interpretation and an instrumental version.
The singing is provided by Katesina Knunkova and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremic and Jaroslav Krsek are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
The Czech national singing is considered to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously told the Czech public radio station, he chose singers' solo versions with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have a good diction, so that one can understand the lyrics, let them sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The singing Kde domov m'j first resounded in 1834 on the plates of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of the States) in Fidlovaika (Kermesse des favotiers), Czech original piece by Josef Kajeton Tyl, accompanied by the music of Frantyek Okroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of the Checoslaovaquia in 1918, the first verse became naturally an integral part of the national anthem.
He remained one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
