Sudetens called for a referendum in the US
Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that the United States should be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho-esk-v-deck-knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the employers of the United States of America.
In 1945, some Sudeten German groups were allegedly addressing the President of the United States with such a desire.
This follows, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jiho-esk-Vodeck-Knihovna.
In the letter, Germans from Krumlov asked the US President not to allow the 'Surhizoster' (region of forests south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "Nobody, to whom the fate of the zumava is close to".
Given that the rallying of Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only brutality, unreliable attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter are asking the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of the zumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign State to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," says in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for vengeance of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in the city, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the US, or to live under the employers of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the post-war history, appear somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to preside over that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them had such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the US and Britain to achieve a certain kind of autonomy for Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who was born in the town of Budjovice, confirmed this.
During the war, he was, as a German of Budjovice, who was engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region at the end of the war, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him for the Czech language.
'They believed that once back home, the Czech would be profitable to them,' said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war considered that, following the Bene decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
