Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (died September 25) states that "in 1946, he had resumed his studies in economic history, in Oxford, and in 1950 became a member of Houblon-Norma research, while he was doing a BSc, an MA and a PhD".
That's what comes from Woodruff's author's letter in Beyond Nab End, but it's not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was Professor of Economic History at the University of Nottingham, and at the same time completed a PhD thesis on the British plastics industry, under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers; it was later published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
In the 1950s and 51s in the United States, he studied at Norman Hugs, and in the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
