"I photograph the master out of the stage to capture elements of his character"
No heels, no hills.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where one discovers intimate gestures and stolen eyes artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Gunther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some staging with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less well-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Mois de la Photographie Fleender, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, bigger every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of the personality of these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of flamenco stars."
With the "Sing Popular du Mines" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, remember the classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "Music with very traditional roots that evolve and that surprises every day".
It is not about dancing or singing per se, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and magic was the constant of this work that we present these days at the El Fotatta gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book collecting portraits on display at the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sports" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph people's portraits, know them and be able to enter their lives for a more or less long time.
I think in photography portraits are the most difficult genre.
You're in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or who only leave you for a few minutes so you can take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try that my ideas become reality."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the Galerie El Fot-mata, located at number 20 on Rue de la Mata (a street parallel to the Peuplerai d'Hercules) which will be open until 16 October.
