The 'bead car' which avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has drawn inspiration, this time, from nature, in particular bees.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating bee theft, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. made this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Research in Advanced Science and Technology at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director-General for Public Relations for Technology and Research and the Development of Mark Management, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan Security Shield.
This robot will allow the branded vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that closely resembles the Nissan security shield.
But the most important is the bee-compound eyes, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly uninterruptedly within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers developed what is known as a laser lock (Laser Range Finder).
The latter detects obstacles which are over a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"At the moment it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by switching its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Displacement Laboratory and main engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards or diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions such as bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotational function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device must only process information and act according to this data.
It does not need to keep the information or the intuitive logic of prior maneuvers, which is why it can operate continuously with only a few dozen memory KBs.
It may surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This represents the first development of new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in a decade or so after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the road.
