Sleeping
A few children speak during the night.
I don't relate to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens, it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquia.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Sure there's more than one who speaks during the night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence
They are often linked to other sleeping alterations such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enureas (paeping in beds) or sleepwalkering, but this is not always the case.
As we said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stress or overexcitation situations.
Anyway, it's a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
