Interview - Blood returned to safe
Haéma-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Most importantly, it regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public lorry, the Government of Canada established a public inquiry in February 1994, presided over by Justice Horace Krever, which sought to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to ensure that such a disaster did not recur.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Dr Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said, proudly stating that in early 2008, nearly 94 percent of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which tells the one that has been holding the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was then based on one of the main recommendations, according to which, when it is not known and a serious disease can result from this, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterised by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are introduced.
In April 1999, blood was therefore denied to persons who had resided in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
However, a few years ago, it was shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied makes sense."
In 1999 a much more sensitive technique for testing for HIV was found on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests, which make it possible to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used hitherto were based.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the moment when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period may have been reduced to less than one week.
The risk of some donors being infected without knowing this has been substantially reduced and that they cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV.
'In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hama-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, this will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product.
I believe that we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health,' says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just later, last year appeared on the island of Réunion, the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", Dr Décary continues before pointing out that, in addition to security supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
"Needs are rising because the population is ageing.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to recharge red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the network of blood donors, which accounts for only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.'
However, any healthy person who is 18 years of age and older who meets the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
'With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
As today's life is so unbridled, there is rarely time to spend an hour donating blood," Francine Décary docks.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year,' says Dr Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed not to have access to it", because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
