Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its 17 September edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Senior Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Continuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company sued six million for three authors and a small, penniless publishing house, with the aim of launching a "transparent public debate".
While it was true that judges were independent and impartial, it was not the truth they tried, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not through truncheons.
It was therefore enough for the miner to open their books, their files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support for Black Canada authors as a perdu the hand.
Perhaps Mr. Could Garver explain how he can both request a 'public' debate while disregarding the views of the same audience?
In the vice-presidential world, it seems that this word refers only to grtuating lawyers and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so above all because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is prepared to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not as part of what many perceive as a gag prosecution (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a letter with a letter to Blacks Canada authors urging them to cease using this term...).
Beyond the surreal speech of Mr. Garver, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the search for truth, which is essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to summon copies of credible sources and to the debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are unpleasant to the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, on pain of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
It has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been known to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to academia, as is to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms that limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Get Ridge
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the USD 700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It provides, inter alia, for better control by elected representatives of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new arrangements to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, and a right of control over the salaries paid to the directors of rescued companies.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards a market-effective understanding," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done in such a way as to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"That's the fundamental point: if we don't do that, the trauma, chaos and disruptions to Americans' daily lives will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had sprinted in the last few hours for fear of the effect that another failure would have on the mood of investors.
The limited time agreed was the opening of markets this morning.
Assumed late in the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather in favour of the understanding, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that one was forced to arrive at that end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added certain provisions to the agreement, including allowing homeowners to hold their homes and on the salaries of government-suppressed company executives.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be welcomed.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
Asked about another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, said, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad outlines I've read that it's something that we're all going to have to digest and with which we're going to be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,' he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back the bad debts, risky and unsaleable assets of US financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
After 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that initially led to the collapse of sub-prime mortgages before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze on liquidity and the disgress of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had derailed the first draft of the deal last week.
It is believed that they have emerged from this impasse since the Democrats accepted that certain “toxic” assets of troubled companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round up the angles for everyone in Congress, it was also added a provision stating that if the government were to face losses for five years with that programme, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which another EUR 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be approved by another congressional vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will win stakes in the rescued companies that will earn dividends in the event of a profit that it can resell when the turmoil is over.
The Federal Government will have the possibility to delay the foreclosure procedures for housing attached to the housing loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance pay paid to the directors of the companies affected.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, there continued to speak out against this project yesterday, both in the Republican and Democratic sides.
"Obviously, Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that benefits from taxpayers."
A leader of a small group in Congress nicknamed "the caucus of sceptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
'Four eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to say to us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to look carefully at the way to go,' he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
Following an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had given up its competitor in full sinking since it lost EUR 2 billion (USD 2.9 billion) in the crisis in risky mortgages in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, a voting right is regained in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, across the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalising another bank that had been plagued by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from the Bank of Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion (USD 75.5 billion) of home loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would purchase the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second largest bank, after Northern Rock, which the British government is expected to nationalize since the beginning of the financial crisis.
