The psychology of competition: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the commodity.
Neurological and economics researchers at New York University have successfully uncovered the neurological and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be outpaced in this type of competition, such as an eBay auction, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw up a neurological schema of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analysed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the outcast of a third, the whole being under the brainstem, called striatum, moved intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
