Hepatitis: When should we see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that 100 miles are infected with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are being treated. This is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (permum, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach upset and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes on a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to reach the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneaks awayly destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing.
The infection is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed them.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, so the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, to the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
