Smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What better method would be to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, except for the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the initial strategic idea to Nissan's engineers, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a robotic mini-car, a BR23C, self-powered, bio-inspired, system, which it equipped with bee qualities, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system that could avoid all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee is its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks very much like our safe protective shell - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
The latter identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is proceeding entirely instinctively.
'If this were not the case, the mini auto robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where, for the moment, the collision is considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Opposite bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, the acceleration as well as the slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentrate, making their lifetime longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and to react with the intuitive logic based on the data from previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need a memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instantaneous avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter mass-produced cars within the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles in its path.
