A fox in the chicken house
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with an applicant, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of the information concerning the prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the agreement of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting his chicken house to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug prescriptions, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital dependent in the event of damage on the state of health of the customer, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after they had seen the results.
Over the past decade, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies, data on the person's drug purchases within the 18 months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease suffers the person and what his or her state of health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this programme are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer apart from the paperwork. However, tiny problems may still occur.
Among the disadvantages of this programme is the fact that a medicine can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flushes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in data research and analysis. They must ask the patient for the authorisation before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their shortcomings in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory analysis results, and link them to drug consumption data. In this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the patients' state of health.
More and more companies have access to data, and monitoring of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on the expansion of the supervisory circle of authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and therefore further developed his programme, which would condition the data transmission of the data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
This is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
So, and ultimately, chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
