The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
That is the goal of various American research centres, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measured barely 2.5 square centimeters, researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
The American journal Science published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a pile of spaghetti." Explicits at the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs, which provide the animal with a perfect adherent.
Testing on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time that it 'get off the wall easily,' explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton University's engineering faculty.
MARCHER ON THE MURS? – "This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Perhaps it is, but researchers are thinking of much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, given that carbon nanotubes are heat and electric current conductive.
Other applications could be aerospace engineering.
Right now, no superhero.
RESEARCH - The University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to the search for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive of microfibers such as hair, which self-cleans dust during movement over an area to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Look out for grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because they are bleathing and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital drugs, alter the absorption or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices whether they are, in a box or fresh, if combined with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he sounds a new alarm: it only takes a glass of grapefruit juice, orange and apples to reduce their health.
Grapefruit juice has already been strongly criticised because it is held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antistamin and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
RISK-- It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which gave the news in a two-year-old newsletter, alerting doctors and patients not to be under-assessed the danger deriving from this mix and to pay attention to what is being used, if medicines are taken such as Diazepam or Méthadone.
