Students who were victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market is not in crisis
According to the Sunia's latest survey, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding whole categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families from whom they have to support - explains the head of the Sunia consultancy, Laura Mariani, in these cities, the strong demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of widespread increase has begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also include a series of violations: free, unregistered contracts, no rental limits, sub-rentals.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are needed to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about EUR 450; for a single room, we range from a minimum of EUR 650 (Nerre Ban zone), to an average value of 800 (Lambiata, Udine, and Fiera area) to a maximum of EUR 900 (Vittoria area)
In Florence, an average bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, one room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a double bed, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 euros for a double bed.
Slightly lower values (EUR 550 for one single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiens and Cinecittà).
We can only save if you move away in the peripheral areas: EUR 300 for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a single one, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for a bed, it takes 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old Paradiso cinema, cities eliminate historical halls.
Historical cinemas close in favour of the Multiplex.
"A city without movie theater is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image presented by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major urban centres of Italy, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of the marginalization of cinemas, with the birth of large multi-rooms on the periphery, and the death of the mono rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that we consider to be inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical and memory-laden places, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of the path and so many emotions," observes the director of the Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix de la Jure de Cannes, and whoLost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of shopkeepers, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have paid mainly the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 single-the-nat cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exploitation has developed irrationally", observes Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the state's anterior debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from a ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
Support for the sector would require between EUR 16 and 18 million per year.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, concerned by these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-room cinemas in historic centres and on the outskirts.
Among the planned standards are tax-care measures for managers and public benefits in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special parking rates and in some car parks.
"I like this initiative," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna setting up other measures.
It is clear, however, that, in order to contrast the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Paradiso Cinema" that I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side not to see the panels blackened by dust.
